lctech f1c200s: enable UART0 on PE0/PE1 for the ESP32 BT HCI

BT-over-SPI proved flaky on the shared link (HCI command timeouts while
WLAN runs error-free), so Bluetooth moves to its own UART: the ESP32 runs
the release's esp32/spi+uart firmware (HCI H4 on its UART1 @ 921600, TX
IO5 / RX IO18; its CTS IO23 is strapped to GND since the host side has no
flow-control pins), wired to UART0 on PE0/PE1 (header P1).

The CherryPi schematic routes the CH340 USB-serial to PE0/PE1, but
production Lctech boards demonstrably route it to PA2/PA3 (the console,
serial0 = &uart1, works there) -- PE0/PE1 are free. The serial1 alias
pins the device name ttyS1 for the hciattach in `bt on`.

--- a/arch/arm/boot/dts/allwinner/suniv-f1c200s-lctech-pi.dts
+++ b/arch/arm/boot/dts/allwinner/suniv-f1c200s-lctech-pi.dts
@@ -17,6 +17,11 @@
 
 	aliases {
 		serial0 = &uart1;
+		/* ttyS1: BT HCI to the ESP32 (H4 at 921600, hciattach'd by
+		 * `bt on`). The CherryPi schematic routes the CH340 to these
+		 * pins, but production boards demonstrably use PA2/PA3, so
+		 * PE0/PE1 are free on header P1. */
+		serial1 = &uart0;
 		/* Fixed bus number 1: the esp-hosted-ng driver attaches its
 		 * spi_board_info by bus number (spi_busnum_to_master(1)). */
 		spi1 = &spi1;
@@ -71,6 +76,12 @@
 	status = "okay";
 };
 
+&uart0 {
+	pinctrl-names = "default";
+	pinctrl-0 = <&uart0_pe_pins>;
+	status = "okay";
+};
+
 &uart1 {
 	pinctrl-names = "default";
 	pinctrl-0 = <&uart1_pa_pins>;
